definition.value: An alpha-amino-acid residue derived from O(4)-phospho-L-tyrosine.
An alpha-amino-acid residue derived from S-hydroxy-L-cysteine.
An alpha-amino-acid residue anion derived from 3-sulfino-L-alanine(1-).
An alpha-amino-acid residue anion derived from S-phospho-L-cysteine(2-).
An alpha-amino-acid residue cation derived from N(6),N(6)-dimethyl-L-lysine(1+).
An alpha-amino-acid residue anion derived from O-phosphonato-L-threonine(2-).
An alpha-amino-acid residue anion derived from O(4)-phosphonato-L-tyrosine(2-)
An alpha-amino-acid residue derived from 4-methyl-2-pyrroline-5-carboxylic acid.
The (S)-enantiomer of azetidine-2-carboxylic acid.
An alpha-amino-acid residue derived from 3-selenino-L-alanine
An alpha-amino-acid residue anion that is the conjugate base of 3-selenino-L-alanine residue, arising from deprotonation of the selenino group.
An alkyl diphosphate where the alkyl group is specified as (E)-2-methylgeranyl.

A peptide anion that is the conjugate base of L-Ala-gamma-D-Glu-meso-Dap-D-Ala, arising from deprotonation of the the three carboxy groups and protonation of both amino groups; major species at pH 7.3.
An organophosphate oxoanion resulting from deprotonation of the three diphosphate OH groups of (E)-2-methylgeranyl diphosphate.
A dicarboxylic acid dianion arising from deprotonation of both carboxy groups of 4-carboxy-2-hydroxymuconate semialdehyde hemiacetal; major species at pH 7.3.
A glucotetrose in which the four D-glucose residues are connected by alpha(1->4) linkages.
An bornane monoterpenoid comprising isoborneol carrying a 2-methyl substituent (the 1R,2R,4R-diastereomer).
A maltotetraose tetrasaccharide in which the glucose residue at the reducing end is in the pyranose ring form and has alpha configuration at the anomeric carbon atom.
An alkylamino group derived from methyl L-cysteinate.
A phytofluene having (E)-double bonds at the 6-, 12-, 14-, 18-, 22- and 26 positions and (Z)-double bonds at the 10- and 16-positions.
A trisaccharide comprised of three D-glucose residues connected by alpha(1->4) linkages.
An acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of Co-A with the carboxylic acid group of sulfoacetic acid.
A maltotriose trisaccharide in which the glucose residue at the reducing end is in the aldehydo open-chain form.
An acyl-CoA oxoanion arising from deprotonation of the phosphate, diphosphate and sulfonate OH groups of sulfoacetyl-CoA; major species at pH 7.3.
A lipid-rich mixture containing glycerol, fatty acids, phosphoric acid and other components.
A glucopentose comprised of five D-glucose residues connected by alpha(1->4) linkages.
A lipid A oxoanion obtained via deprotonation of the carboxy and phosphate OH groups of glucosyl-(heptosyl)2-(KDO)2-lipid A; major species at pH 7.3.
A lipid A oxoanion obtained via deprotonation of the carboxy and phosphate OH groups of glucosyl-heptosyl-4-phosphoheptosyl-(KDO)2-lipid A
A lipid A oxoanion obtained via deprotonation of the carboxy and phosphate OH groups of glucosyl-(heptosyl)2-4-phosphoheptosyl-(KDO)2-lipid A.
A lipid A oxoanion obtained via deprotonation of the carboxy and phosphate OH groups of glucosyl-heptosyl-(phosphoheptosyl)2-(KDO)2-lipid A.
A lipid A oxoanion obtained via deprotonation of the carboxy and phosphate OH groups of galactosyl-glucosyl-heptosyl-(phosphoheptosyl)2-(KDO)2-lipid A
A lipid A oxoanion obtained via deprotonation of the carboxy and phosphate OH groups of galactosyl-(glucosyl)2-(heptosyl)3-(KDO)2-lipid A-bisphosphate.
A lipid A oxoanion obtained via deprotonation of the carboxy and phosphate OH groups of galactosyl-(glucosyl)3-(heptosyl)3-(KDO)2-lipid A-bisphosphate.
A lipid A oxoanion obtained via deprotonation of the carboxy and phosphate OH groups of lipid A-core.
A member of the class of uridines that is uridine in which the hydrogen at position 5 of the pyrimidine ring is substituted by a 2-amino-2-oxoethyl group.
A maltopentaose pentasaccharide in which the glucose residue at the reducing end is in the aldehydo open-chain form.
A glucohexaose comprised of six D-glucose residues connected by alpha(1->4) linkages.
A heptasaccharide comprised of seven D-glucose residues connected by alpha(1->4) linkages.
A maltoheptaose heptasaccharide in which the glucose residue at the reducing end is in the aldehydo open-chain form.
A dicarboxylic acid comprising 2-hydroxy-2H-pyran having two carboxy groups located at the 4- and 6-positions.
A deoxypentose that is aldehydo-D-ribose in which the hydroxy group at position 5 is substituted by a hydrogen.
A L-serine derivative consisting of L-serine having a 1-glycerophospho group attached to the side-chain hydroxy function.
A tetradecenoyl-CoA having cis-tetradec-3-enoyl as the S-acyl group.
A tetrapeptide comprising L-alanyl, gamma-D-glutamyl, meso-diaminopimelyl and L-alanine units in a linear sequence.
A lipid A derivative having an alpha-D-Glc-(1->3)-L-alpha-D-Hep-(1->3)-L-alpha-D-Hep-(1->5)-[alpha-Kdo-(2->4)]-alpha-Kdo moiety attached to the free primary hydroxy group of lipid A.
A lipid A derivative having an alpha-D-Glc-(1->3)-L-alpha-D-Hep-(1->3)-4-O-H2PO3-L-alpha-D-Hep-(1->5)-[alpha-Kdo-(2->4)]-alpha-Kdo moiety attached to the free primary hydroxy group of lipid A.
An N-propionylated alpha-(2->8)-linked homosialopolysaccharide consisting of four alpha-D-N-propionylneuraminyl residues joined by (2->8) linkages (i.e. [8)-alpha-Neu5Pr-(2->]n where n = 4).
An N-propionylated alpha-(2->8)-linked homosialopolysaccharide consisting of five alpha-D-N-propionylneuraminyl residues joined by (2->8) linkages (i.e. [8)-alpha-Neu5Pr-(2->]n  where n = 5).
